40|$|The Twenty-sixth Congress of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union {{comprehensively}} {{examined the}} current {{problems in the}} economic and social development of the USSR. It articulated long-range goals stemming from <b>socialism's</b> inherent objective necessity to raise the living standard of all people on a systematic basis and indicated ways of reaching those goals under present conditions. ...|$|R
50|$|The Kaliflower {{community}} {{was founded on}} the same spiritual and economic principles as the Diggers: shared property and labor and the liberation of culture from commercialism. The commune's members were inspired by John Humphrey Noyes, founder of the Oneida Community, a socialist commune that existed in New York in the 1840s, and his book, The History of American <b>Socialisms.</b>|$|R
